This paper is likely to belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) category as it focuses on cross-media retrieval, which is a highlighting research topic in the multimedia area. Additionally, the paper proposes a deep neural network approach for feature representation and comparison functions learning, which is a common technique in computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The paper also mentions the use of similarity metrics and pairwise constraints, which are common in information retrieval (cs.IR) and machine learning (cs.LG).
